@NODE "INTRO" "InTroDuCTiOn"
@TOC "MAIN"
(-) InTRoDuCTiOn  (-)

mY cOOL dIARY, born almost as a joke, has been accepted well and utilised by the
amiga  users  so  that  a  new  version  had to be made to replace the older and
outdated ones.. The more outdated part was certainly the  GUI,  that  was  coded
using  the  old OS2 standards, and now it has been rewritten 100% using MUI..
If you already know or maybe even use, mY cOOL dIARY, go and try  out  this  new
3.00  version,  if  on  the  contrary you're new to this program, here it goes a
short introduction..
mY cOOL dIARY is a little database made to  be  fast,  easytouse  and  efficent.
There  are  no  many  options,  just the essential ones to store and handle some
records, be them phone numbers, addresses, programs, videotapes or whatever else
you like..
Compared to the old ones, this version is very much faster because it  has  been
rewritten  from  scratch  and it has even become more userfriendly (we've worked
hard on it).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "USAGE" "UsAGe"
@TOC "MAIN"
(-) UsAGE (-)

No many things to say, because a program like this, claimed to be  userfriendly,
should have no need to be explained in all his functions.
So here they are the most important things. In the window title there is  a sort
of status  bar that shows the number of records in your diary (database) and two
flags: M and C.
M stands for modified and it is turned on every time datas are modified and  not
saved,  while C stands for crypted and it is turned on when you are working with
a crypted diary that will be encoded with the password you have defined  in  the
prefs menu.
You can choose to save a diary in the  mCD  proprietary  format  (save  option),
crypted  or  uncrypted,  or  in a plain ASCII format (save ascii option) so that
you'll be able to print it or view it with a text editor.
You can  define  with  the  DEFAULT  tooltype  a  default  diary  that  will  be
automatically loaded when mCD is run.
If you run from CLI you can enter the default diary as the argument.


@ENDNODE

